iant of   Carleton   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Carleton","meanings":["English (northern and eastern England): variant of   Carlton  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted in Northern Ireland as an Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cairealláin</b>, see   Carolan   2."]},{"name":"Charlton","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from North Charlton or Charlton near Bellingham (both Northumberland) or from any of the many other places so named (there are over ninety examples in England), from Old English <i>Ceorlatūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":51,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":60,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":71,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Carlton Sr was born in 1498, in Wakefield, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 son with William Carlton Sr."},"et":{"1498–":"1498–Surnud","1497–Male":"1497–Surnud","1538–1583":"1538–1583","1498–Female":"1498–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1497":"1497","1583":"1583","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","Wakefield, Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1498–":"1498–Kuollut","1497–Male":"1497–Kuollut","1538–1583":"1538–1583","1498–Female":"1498–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1497":"1497","1583":"1583","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","Wakefield, Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1498–":"1498–Décédée","1497–Male":"1497–Décédé","1538–1583":"1538–1583","1498–Female":"1498–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1497":"1497","1583":"1583","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","Wakefield, Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs William Carlton Sr est née en 1498, à Wakefield, Everwyck, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec William Carlton Sr."},"de":{"1498–":"1498–Verstorben","1497–Male":"1497–Verstorben","1538–1583":"1538–1583","1498–Female":"1498–Verstorben","1569":"